snippet.textDisplay: Net neutrality was repealed and within 2 weeks verizon made an announcement to roll out fiber in my area and we went from paying optimum 100 a month to for 40/5 to 60 a month for 200/40 but once I heard verizon was offering 960/880 for 70 a month I swapped real fast and I couldn't be happier. Net neutrality protected optimums 40/5 plan by not allowing competition. Sorry but a lot of the fearmongering around NN's repeal was because the inadequate ISP's were afraid of competition, not because it was bad for the consumer. ATT offering their service capless free on their network made sense, it is theirs after all. For example I can watch pretty much everything but HBO on my tmobile plan with no caps, so if that was a major thing for a consumer, they may switch carriers. This is how the free market works. If ATT lost enough customers to tmobile over this, then they'd be forced to either cut their prices or offer the capless streaming to all. But instead california feels the need to make laws to intervene putting competition to a halt and punishing the consumer as a result, because time and time again, california has proven to not care about its citizens.

One thing to Note about GeForce Now - the wording in the email is as follows:

Maintaining your Benefit
To keep the Founders for Life benefit, you must maintain your on-going paid Founders membership without interruption. That requires you keep your payment information current and make timely payments. You must also use the service in accordance with the terms of use.

If for any reason your paid Founders membership ends, you make a billing modification or if there is a termination, the benefit is forfeited and cannot be restarted. 

So it's not just if you cancel - it sounds like if you miss a payment and they end it for you - which, during COVID-19 times, is horseshit.

snippet.textDisplay: Good for competition if Intel is making a major move into the realm of graphics beyond low end iGPUs. And so far the marketing is better than what Intel has done in recent times which is just rehashing the same old 14nm products, cherry picking benchmarks and ranting about "AMD" and "our imitators." Perhaps Mr. Gelsinger is starting to turn things around? But at this point it doesn't even matter if they have to make their first graphics cards on 14nm. They basically just have to have mass availability and be able to beat the GeForce 710, as nothing newer/better is available.
